	   <tr><td colspan=2>Rolling makes things more equal and is the most fair.<br><br>On a very good item like this rolling from all the classes it is best for who would actually wear it all the time would be the best system. <br><br>For one thing, though I said "very good item" its really not a class defining item that will give someone a huge advantage or make them far more powerful for the guild like some fantastic weapon or very high haste item. It is simply a very nice item for the classes who would gain the most benefit from it. I see class defining items more as things which a guild hand picks who gets while just very nice items for several classes are more likely to be rolled on.<br><br>There are a lot of problems with deciding to give everything to the people who "put the most effort into helping the guild." Also, far too often, who puts the most effort is pretty subjective and based upon favoritism, friendship and even (as I have seen) someone's perceived real life sex and charismatic/flirtacious in game nature. I've seen all those things happen in many different guilds.<br><br>Therefore even pretty darn uber guilds often turn to a rolling system especially for an area like Veeshan's Peak on some items when pretty much everyone there took the time to get the key so they obviously have been of help to a guild. The people who come the most or "do the most for the guild" end up being rewarded the most whether there is rolling or not. Rolling on some items just gives people who can't always be there some slim chance to have a couple nice things and feel that there is some reason for them even belonging.<br><br>A guild where only the people who "help the most" get the best items is a guild where only real life bums and people who leech off their parents get rewarded. It is also a guild where anyone without as much free time soon would feel alienated and leave. <br><br>You don't miss the people who come sometimes until none of them are around anymore and you find that you don't have enough people to do X area. The sometimes people are important.<br><br>Another system I've seen is taking the top several people from the applicable classes and letting them roll. <br><br>The thing is that the most uber people in a guild can't do a damn thing all by themselves. If items are always hand selected for them (usually by others as uber as them.. a kind of "scratch my back I'll scratch yours" system) the rest of the people whose backs they ride on will eventually get wise.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
